abstract = {4 elements of studying life histories: 1) Demography: connects variation in age and size specific variation in fecundity and mortality to variation in fitness: compares the strength of natural selection on different traits. 2) Quantitative genetics and reaction norms: statistical model of effects of many genes acting at once. 3) Trade-offs: physiology contributes insights into the mechanisms that cause trade-offs. 4) Lineage-specific effects Demography Interpretations of equations and symbols in demography differ for classical demography and life history theory. IN CD they represent whole organisms in the popn and their age-specific birth and death schedules. Same equations and symbols in LHT refer to effects of gene substitution. A population with a constant birth and death schedule will attain a stable age distribution and then grow exponentially at a constant rate. The rate at which it grows can be calculated from the Euler-Lotka equation. Assumes stable age distribution and constant mortality and fertility rates. Popn in stable age distribution may be increasing, decreasing or unchanging but the proportion of organisms in each age class is stable. Generation time is the average age of mothers of in a popn with stable age dist. Williams (1957, 1966) divided reproductive value of female into 2 components: births in current age class and reproductive value in next age class (residual reproductive value). But RRV is not just reproductive value of female in next age class - need to add 2 components: probability of surviving to next age class given female has survived to current age class, and discount term necessary becasue popn maybe growing. Therefore cost of reprouction takes 2 main forms: increase in present reproduction may have negative influence on surviving to next age class, or on reproductive value of next age class, or both. One central idea in LHT is that current and residual reproductive value should be so balanced that in every age class fitness is maximal. Calculating this balance for all age classes predicts the distribution of reproductive effort across the entire lifetime. Quantitative genetics and reaction norms Whereas demography analyses the phenotypic sources of variation in fitness that produce natural selection, quantitative genetics and reaction norms are used to analyse the genetic variation that conditions the response to selection. The heritabilities of fitness components are lower than heritabilities of other traits but considerable genetic variation for LH traits is maintained in nature. Sometimes heritabilities of LH traits are large. Five explanations for this: mutation-selection balance, genotype by environment interactions in heterogeneous environments, negative genetic covariance, gene flow and flat fitness profiles. Quantitative genetics deals with continuously varying traits - quantitative, metric or polygenic traits. Traits that clearly separate into distinct classes are called Mendelian. Reaction norm is the set of phenotypes produced by a single genotype across a range of environmental conditions. Additive genetic variation is the variation in the breeding values of individuals in the popn. Breeding value is twice the deviation of an individual's progeny from the popn mean when it is mated at random with a sample of the popn. Non-additive effects include dominance, interactions with other loci (epistasis) and maternal effects in some experimental designs. Trade-offs Distinguish between physiological trade-offs - energy allocation between 2 or more functions competing for the same resources within a single individual and evolutionary trade-offs - defined by manipulation expts on phenotypes and by correlated response to selection on popns. Best studied TOs are between current reproduction and survival, current and future reproduction, reproduction and growth, reproduction and condition and number and quality of offspring. 2 methods for measuring TOs: 1) select on one trait and measure correlated responses on the other - artifical selection expts 2) manipulate phenotype and study consequences in same individuals - eg, expts on clutch and egg size Red deer: adult mortality higher in females nursing offspring. Age dependent - only significant in females over 10 yrs. Principle of allocation may be affected by: 1) if resource other than energy is limiting eg time or mineral nutrient, energy allocations do not TO 2) if energy is limiting but functions differ in their sensitivity to variation in the amount of energy allocated, then though TOs are always there, will be insignificantly small under some circs and large under others 3) if certain amounts of energy are always allocated to given activities, then allocations are made with what is left over},
