les. To differentiate$\backslash$nbetween canalization of adult survival and frailty/selective mortality$\backslash$nof juveniles, we included five populations of small mammals. We then$\backslash$nfound a negative relationship between the relative potential impact$\backslash$nof age-dependent survival on fitness and the relative variability$\backslash$nof age-dependent survival, especially for populations faced with$\backslash$nhigh environmental variation. This remained true after correcting$\backslash$nfor differences in mean survival of juveniles and adults and was$\backslash$nindependent of phylogeny. Although more data are required to extend$\backslash$nthe hypothesis to other taxonomic groups, we conclude that available$\backslash$ndata support the idea that adult survival of ungulates is canalized$\backslash$nagainst temporal variation. Therefore, contrasted responses of juvenile$\backslash$nand prime-age survival to environmental variaton in ungulates may$\backslash$nbe adaptive and could be viewed as a bet-hedging strategy.},
